<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a network port number?", answer: "A port number is a 16-bit unsigned integer (0 to 65535) that identifies a specific process or service on a networked device. When data arrives at a server, the operating system uses the destination port number to route the traffic to the correct application. Port 80 directs traffic to the web server, port 22 to the SSH daemon, and port 5432 to PostgreSQL. Without port numbers, a single IP address could only run one network service at a time." },
  { question: "What is the difference between TCP and UDP?", answer: "TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) is connection-oriented. It establishes a session between sender and receiver, guarantees delivery, and ensures packets arrive in order. UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is connectionless. It sends packets without establishing a session and does not guarantee delivery or ordering. TCP is used for web traffic (HTTP/HTTPS), email (SMTP), and file transfers (FTP) where reliability is critical. UDP is used for DNS lookups, streaming, and real-time applications where speed matters more than guaranteed delivery." },
  { question: "What are well-known ports?", answer: "Well-known ports are the range from 0 to 1023. They are assigned by IANA (Internet Assigned Numbers Authority) to widely-used protocols like HTTP (80), HTTPS (443), SSH (22), and SMTP (25). On Unix-like systems, binding to a well-known port typically requires root privileges. Registered ports (1024-49151) are assigned to specific services by IANA upon request. Dynamic or ephemeral ports (49152-65535) are used temporarily by client applications for outgoing connections." },
  { question: "Why is port 443 important?", answer: "Port 443 is the default port for HTTPS, which is HTTP encrypted with TLS. Nearly all modern web traffic uses port 443 because browsers, search engines, and security standards require TLS encryption. Websites that serve content only on port 80 (unencrypted HTTP) are flagged as insecure by browsers. Port 443 is essential for protecting user data, login credentials, and payment information during transit." },
  { question: "How do I check which ports are open on my server?", answer: "On Linux, use the command ss -tlnp or netstat -tlnp to list all TCP ports that are listening along with the process that owns each one. On macOS, use lsof -iTCP -sTCP:LISTEN. On Windows, use netstat -an | findstr LISTENING. For external scanning, tools like nmap can probe a remote server to discover which ports are accepting connections. Always close ports that are not needed to reduce your attack surface." }
]) %>

